22–Male":"1422–Deceased","1471–1544":"1471–1544","1358–1400":"1358–1400","1358–Female":"1358–Deceased","1358":"1358","1544":"1544","1411":"1411","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1433":"1433","1387":"1387","1471":"1471","Rossinton, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Angmering, Sussex, England":"Angmering, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","<Of, Angmering, Sussex, England>":"Angmering, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cook","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cookson","meanings":["English (Lancashire): from Middle English <i>cok</i> ‘cook’ or the surname <i>Cook</i> + <i>son</i>, denoting either ‘son of (the) cook’ or ‘son of (a man called) Cook’. See   Cook  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Coke","meanings":["English: variant of   Cook   or   Cocke  .","Americanized form of German   Koke   or   Koch  ."]},{"name":"Kuhar","meanings":["Slovenian and Croatian: occupational name for a cook, from <i>kuhar</i>, a derivative of <i>kuhati</i> ‘to cook’. Compare   Cook  .","Americanized form of Slovak <b>Kuchár</b> ‘cook’ (see   Kuchar  ) and of its Ukrainian and Rusyn cognate <b>Kukhar</b>."]},{"name":"Cooke","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."]},{"name":"Kew","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>queu</i>, <i>keu</i>, <i>kieu</i>, <i>cu</i> ‘cook’, i.e. one who sold cooked meat, keeper of an eating house.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Caieu, a lost town in northern France, in the vicinity of Boulogne-sur-Mer.","Irish: shortened Ulster variant of   McHugh  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Cook was born in 1387, in Angmering, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Henry Coke, was 29 and his mother, Mrs Henry Coke, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs John Cook. He died in Sussex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1387–":"1387–Surnud","1387–Male":"1387–Surnud","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","1411–1433":"1411–1433","1422–Male":"1422–Surnud","1471–1544":"1471–1544","1358–1400":"1358–1400","1358–Female":"1358–Surnud","1358":"1358","1544":"1544","1411":"1411","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1433":"1433","1387":"1387","1471":"1471","Rossinton, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Angmering, Sussex, England":"Angmering, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","<Of, Angmering, Sussex, England>":"Angmering, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1387–":"1387–Kuollut","1387–Male":"1387–Kuollut","1387–Female":"1387–Kuollut","1411–1433":"1411–1433","1422–Male":"1422–Kuo